Customer Holiday Spending¶

1. Dataset Summary¶

This dataset is about customer visit and customer spending for a fashion retailer throughout the year. We want to predict customer spending during holiday season to decide which customer will be targeted for the upcoming holiday season promotion.

The features are:

  • Customer_ID
  • loyalty_flag =
    Indicator if a customer has loyalty membership card
  • Trans_0012 = Total no. of transactions made by customer in last one year (Jan'14 to Dec'14)
  • Visit_0012 =
    Total visits made by a customer to the store in last 1 year
  • SalesAmount_0012 = Total amount spent by a customer in the store in last 1 year
  • Quantity_0012 = Total quantities purchased by a customer in last 1 year
  • Distinct_Items_Bought = Distinct items bought by a customer in last 1 year
  • Days_Since_Customer = Days since customer has purchased loyalty membership card
  • Days_Since_LastVisit = Days since customer last visited the store by the year end 2014
  • Holiday_Sales = Sales made during holiday period (target variable)
  • Avg_Gap_Btw_Vists = Average days gap between two consecutive visits of a customer to the store
  • SKU_1 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (Stock Keeping Unit - Jeans) in last 1 year
  • SKU_2 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (T-Shirts) in last 1 year
  • SKU_3 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (Shirts) in last 1 year
  • SKU_4 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (Formals) in last 1 year
  • SKU_5 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (Shoes) in last 1 year
  • SKU_6 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (New Collection) in last 1 year
  • SKU_7 = Indicator if a customer made purchase in SKU (Accessories) in last 1 year

def check_values(df):
    col_desc = []
    data = {
        'features': [col for col in df.columns],
        'data_type': [df[col].dtype for col in df.columns],
        'nan_total': [df[col].isna().sum() for col in df.columns],
        'nan_pct': [round(df[col].isna().sum()/len(df)*100,2) for col in df.columns],
        'unique': [df[col].nunique() for col in df.columns],
        'values_ex': [df[col].drop_duplicates().sample(df[col].nunique()).values if df[col].nunique() <= 5 else df[col].drop_duplicates().sample(2).values for col in df.columns]
    }
    return pd.DataFrame(data)

Normality test¶

Do normality test using D'Agostino K$^2$ test

$H_0$: data from normal distribution

$H_1$: data not from normal distribution

In [33]:

def rmse(ytrue, ypredicted):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(ytrue, ypredicted))
In [486]:
def cross_validation_multi(estimator, X=X_train_val_prep2):
    kfold = KFold(shuffle=True, random_state=26, n_splits=5)
    cv_score = cross_validate(estimator=estimator, X=X, y=y_train_val, scoring=['neg_mean_squared_error','r2'], cv=kfold, n_jobs=4)
    return cv_score

In [490]:
def plot_cv(estimator, X=X, alphas=np.array([0.01, 0.03, 0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30])):
    # alphas = np.array([0.01, 0.03, 0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30])
    rmse_scores = []
    r2_scores = []
    for alpha in alphas:
        cvs = cross_validation_multi(X=X, estimator=estimator(alpha=alpha))
        rmse_score = np.sqrt(cvs['test_neg_mean_squared_error'].mean()*-1)
        rmse_scores.append(rmse_score)
        r2_score = cvs['test_r2'].mean()
        r2_scores.append(r2_score)
        print(f'alpha ({alpha}): RMSE {round(rmse_score,2)}, r2 {round(r2_score,3)}')
        
    plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,3))
    # plt.figure()
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.lineplot(alphas, rmse_scores, label='RMSE')
    plt.xlabel('alpha')
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    g=sns.lineplot(alphas, r2_scores, label='r2')
    g.set_xlabel('alpha')
    plt.legend()
    # plt.tight_layout()

In [492]:
def plot_learning_curve_scoring(estimator, title, X, y, axes=None, ylim=None, cv=None, scoring=None,
                        n_jobs=None, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    """
    Generate 3 plots: the test and training learning curve, the training
    samples vs fit times curve, the fit times vs score curve.

    Parameters
    ----------
    estimator : estimator instance
        An estimator instance implementing `fit` and `predict` methods which
        will be cloned for each validation.

    title : str
        Title for the chart.

    X : array-like of shape (n_samples, n_features)
        Training vector, where ``n_samples`` is the number of samples and
        ``n_features`` is the number of features.

    y : array-like of shape (n_samples) or (n_samples, n_features)
        Target relative to ``X`` for classification or regression;
        None for unsupervised learning.

    axes : array-like of shape (3,), default=None
        Axes to use for plotting the curves.

    ylim : tuple of shape (2,), default=None
        Defines minimum and maximum y-values plotted, e.g. (ymin, ymax).

    cv : int, cross-validation generator or an iterable, default=None
        Determines the cross-validation splitting strategy.
        Possible inputs for cv are:

          - None, to use the default 5-fold cross-validation,
          - integer, to specify the number of folds.
          - :term:`CV splitter`,
          - An iterable yielding (train, test) splits as arrays of indices.

        For integer/None inputs, if ``y`` is binary or multiclass,
        :class:`StratifiedKFold` used. If the estimator is not a classifier
        or if ``y`` is neither binary nor multiclass, :class:`KFold` is used.

        Refer :ref:`User Guide <cross_validation>` for the various
        cross-validators that can be used here.

    n_jobs : int or None, default=None
        Number of jobs to run in parallel.
        ``None`` means 1 unless in a :obj:`joblib.parallel_backend` context.
        ``-1`` means using all processors. See :term:`Glossary <n_jobs>`
        for more details.

    train_sizes : array-like of shape (n_ticks,)
        Relative or absolute numbers of training examples that will be used to
        generate the learning curve. If the ``dtype`` is float, it is regarded
        as a fraction of the maximum size of the training set (that is
        determined by the selected validation method), i.e. it has to be within
        (0, 1]. Otherwise it is interpreted as absolute sizes of the training
        sets. Note that for classification the number of samples usually have
        to be big enough to contain at least one sample from each class.
        (default: np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 5))
    """
#     if axes is None:
#         _, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 5))
    _, axes = plt.subplots()

    axes.set_title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        axes.set_ylim(*ylim)
    axes.set_xlabel("Training examples")
    axes.set_ylabel("Score")

    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores, fit_times, _ = \
        learning_curve(estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs,
                       train_sizes=train_sizes, scoring=scoring,
                       return_times=True)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)

    # Plot learning curve
    axes.grid()
    axes.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                         train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                         color="r")
    axes.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                         test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                         color="g")
    axes.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
                 label="Training score")
    axes.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
                 label="Cross-validation score")
    axes.legend(loc="best")

    return plt

Lasso Regularization¶

LogisticRegression model with L1 penalty, using different regularization strength. The alpha parameter is the regularization strength. Unlike previous model with Ridge regularization, Lasso gives wider performance range within the same alpha value. RMSE is the lowest in alpha = 0.3 while lower and higher alpha value give higher error.

alpha (30.0): RMSE 23.29, r2 -0.011

Polynomial features with L2 penalty¶

The degree used is 3 for the making of polynomial features from the numerical features. The features are then scaled. Contrary to the previous model with L2 regularization without polynomial features in which the performance decreased after alpha=10 (increasing RMSE), the performance of this model (with polynomial features) stayed the same until alpha=30.

Best Model¶

All of the previous model with feature scaling and regularization performed better than the baseline model. This means that our model performed great in terms of accuracy as shown from the RMSE.

Our ultimate goal is we want to accurately predict customer's spending during holiday season. For this reason, we will choose the model with L1 regularization and alpha = 0.3 since it gives the lowest RMSE and highest $R^2$ of all models above.

When we evaluate this model on the test dataset, we get RMSE of 17.13.

In [519]:
lr_pipe = Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('model', Lasso(alpha=0.3))
])

lr_pipe.fit(X_train_val, y_train_val)
y_pred = lr_pipe.predict(X_test)

print(f'RMSE: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)).round(2)}')

RMSE: 17.13

The figure below shows learning curve for our best model. Note that the score in the y-axis is negative mean squared error, so the higher the score, the better the model performance. The learning curve shows that our model does not suffer from underfitting or overfitting since the error for cross-validation set (test set) is not too low compared to the error for training set.

The highest predictor, SalesAmount_0012, has a coefficient of 10.68. This means for every \$ 1 increase of customer's total purchase during 1 year, assuming all the other factors stay the same, the amount they spend on holiday season increases by \$ 10.68.

Conclusion and Suggestion¶

We have seen that the features in this dataset describe customer's transaction and visit history for a fashion retailer.

We have tried L1 and L2 regularization with different regularization strength. Our best linear regression model with feature scaling and regularization performed better than the baseline model. We evaluated our model on the test set. It turns out that customer's total spending is the best predictor for customer's holiday spending.

The numerical features we used did not all come from normal distribution. Both log and boxcox transformation failed to change them all into normal distribution, so we proceeded with transformation for only two features.

Our model does not suffer from underfitting or overfitting, yet the $R^2$ is low, only 0.43. Addition of other features might be beneficial since more than half of the features we used previously were deemed unimportant when we used Lasso regularization.
